%%TITLE
Presence of human papillomaviruses and p16 expression in hypopharyngeal cancer.
%%ABSTRACT
Patients with hypopharyngeal cancer have a 5-year survival of only 15% to 30%. Human papillomavirus (HPV) is a risk factor and a favorable prognostic factor for oropharyngeal carcinoma and p16 has been suggested as a surrogate marker for HPV-induced cancer. However, few studies have been performed on HPV and p16 in hypopharyngeal cancer.One hundred nine pretreatment hypopharyngeal cancer biopsies were analyzed for presence of HPV and p16 overexpression, and the results were correlated to patient survival.Of 109 tumors, 7 were HPV-positive (4 HPV16) and 18 overexpressed p16. There was some correlation between survival and HPV status, but not with regard to p16 expression. Notably, all patients with HPV16-positive tumors, also overexpressing p16, lived tumor free for more than 3 years.Our results indicate that HPV-induced hypopharyngeal cancer is rare and that p16 is not a suitable biomarker for presence of HPV in this tumor type.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Patients and tumor samples

Patient charts were ana- lyzed and age, patient sex, TNM classification, stage, treat- ment, and survival (5-year overall survival and 5-year disease-free survival) were recorded. Of the 142 patients, pretreatment biopsies from 119 patients were available and the DNA quality of 109 was sufficient for HPV analysis (Table 1). The study was conducted according to ethical permission 2009/1278-31/4 from the Ethical Committee at Karolinska Institutet, Stockholm, Sweden.
DNA extraction and detection of human papillomavirus
DNA extraction was performed by the use of high pure RNA paraffin kit (Roche Molecular Biochemicals, Mann- heim, Germany), as described earlier.23 The presence of HPV DNA was analyzed by the use of a Luminex bead- based assay, as developed by Schmitt et al.24 This assay detects HPV DNA from 24 different HPV types: 13 high- risk types (16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 39, 45, 51, 52, 56, 58, 59,
and 68), 5 possibly high-risk types (26, 53, 66, 73, and
82), and 6 low-risk types (6, 11, 42, 43, 44, and 70) according to the classification by International Agency for Research on Cancer.6 The polymerase chain reaction amplification was performed from 10 and 50 ng extracted DNA and the Luminex assay was performed and the result were evaluated as previously described.25 The Luminex analysis was performed with a MagPix instru- ment from Luminex (Austin, TX). Immunohistochemical analysis of p16
IHC was performed with the p16INK4a primary mono- clonal mouse antihuman p16INK4a antibody (dilution 1:100; clone JC8; Santa Cruz Biotechnology, Santa Cruz, CA) using 4-lm sections of formalin-fixed and paraffin- embedded tissue (for details see Marklund et al26). Stain- ing of tumor samples for p16 was performed and staining was graded according to a 3-tier scale (0: 0%; 1: 1% to
25%; 2: 26% to 74%; and 3: 75% to 100%) and samples with >75% p16-positive tumor cells were considered as p16 positive.26 p16 expression was evaluated by 2 investi- gators (M.R. and A.N.), blinded to treatment outcome, and in case of disagreement, a consensus was made.
Statistical analyses
The correlation between the presence of HPV and over- expression of p16 was evaluated by Fisher’s exact test.

Overall and disease-free survival depending on HPV and p16-status was presented in Kaplan–Meier curves and the log-rank test was used to compare survival curves. Over- all survival was defined as time from the date of diagno- sis to the date of death or last time of follow-up. Disease- free survival was defined as time from end of treatment until the date of disease recurrence (local, regional, or distant recurrence). Death without documented recurrence was censored at the date of death. In the multivariate ana- lyze, a Cox proportional hazards model was used to adjust for covariates. Two-sided p values were reported. These analyses were performed in STATA 10.
